In the group of patients prescribed medication, by comparison, complete cure diabetes was only 1%, and partial - only about 2 per cent.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgical group," say the authors.
The researchers also monitored the а1с hemoglobin levels in the blood, which reflects blood sugar levels in the dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1C test better hold below 7%, "the researchers write.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1C test decreased by approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
In a therapeutic group, however, he remained stable at around 8%.
But the best indicators of glycemic control, but with good levels of hemoglobin A1C test does not reduce mortality rates in five years, according to research by Dr. Chicheng Su and colleagues.
The research team also compared the results of two types of surgical treatment.
For the fifth year, in comparison with the group, polchivshei rukavnuu gastrectomy, the group lost more weight (18.7 kg against heart bypass 14.2 kg), has achieved greater reduction in BMI (7.4 against 5.1) and hemoglobin introduction haemoglobin A1c (HbA1c 3.1% vs. 2.1%), and was also closer to full remission of diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although the new study does not show the benefits of surgical technique in terms of life expectancy after five years, there are research confirm people with excess body weight in Sweden that surgical treatment really leads to an increase in life expectancy, according to Blackstone in Phoenix from College of Medicine, University of Arizona.
According to the Swedish study for people with obesity, have chosen bariatric intervention, the likelihood of dying for 15 years was about 29% lower compared to the group that used more traditional methods.
Despite the fact that the new study found no increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that this reassuring people with a BMI less than 35 interested in such a procedure.
